There are a few different ways you can import and display a large number of images in a React application.

One option is to use a naming convention to organize your images and make it easier to import them. For example, you could name your images `image1.jpg`, `image2.jpg`, etc., and then use a loop to import and display them.

Here's an example of how you might do this:
```
import React from "react";

const images = [];

for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  images.push(require(`./portfolioImages/image${i}.jpg`));
}

export default function Portfolio() {
  return (
    <div>
      {images.map((image, index) => (
        <img key={index} src={image} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```
This code will import and display the images `image1.jpg`, `image2.jpg`, `image3.jpg`, `image4.jpg`, and `image5.jpg` from the `portfolioImages` folder.

