To implement **"Load More Products"** functionality when the user reaches the **bottom of the page** in a **React** application, you can use a combination of **scroll event listeners** and **state management**. Here's a structured and efficient way to do it:

---

## ✅ **Best Way to Load More Products on Scroll (React)**

### 🧩 Key Concepts:
- **Scroll event listener**: Detect when the user scrolls to the bottom.
- **State management**: Track the current page number and fetched data.
- **Debounce or throttle**: Optimize scroll event performance.
- **Infinite scroll**: Load more data as the user scrolls.

---

## 📌 Step-by-Step Implementation

### 1. **Set up your component structure**

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

const ProductList = () => {
  const [products, setProducts] = useState([]);
  const [page, setPage] = useState(1);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [hasMore, setHasMore] = useState(true);
  const observerRef = useRef(null);

  // Fetch products from API
  const fetchProducts = async (page) => {
    if (loading || !hasMore) return;

    setLoading(true);

    try {
      // Replace with your API call
      const res = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/products?page=${page}`);
      const data = await res.json();

      if (data.length === 0) {
        setHasMore(false);
      } else {
        setProducts([...products, ...data]);
        setPage(page + 1);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error fetching products:', error);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  // Detect when user reaches bottom
  useEffect(() => {
    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        if (entries[0].isIntersecting && hasMore && !loading) {
          fetchProducts(page);
        }
      },
      { threshold: 1.0 }
    );

    if (observerRef.current) {
      observer.observe(observerRef.current);
    }

    return () => {
      if (observerRef.current) {
        observer.unobserve(observerRef.current);
      }
    };
  }, [page, hasMore, loading]);

  // Optional: Scroll event listener for fallback
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleScroll = () => {
      if (
        window.innerHeight + document.documentElement.scrollTop ===
        document.documentElement.scrollHeight
      ) {
        if (hasMore && !loading) {
          fetchProducts(page);
        }
      }
    };

    window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
    };
  }, [page, hasMore, loading]);

  return (
    <div>
      {products.map((product, index) => (
        <div key={index}>{product.name}</div>
      ))}
      {loading && <div>Loading...</div>}
      {!hasMore && <div>No more products.</div>}
      <div ref={observerRef} style={{ height: '1px' }}></div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ProductList;
```

---

## ✅ Features of This Implementation:

| Feature | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| **Intersection Observer** | Efficient and modern way to detect when the user reaches the bottom. |
| **Fallback Scroll Event** | Fallback for older browsers or custom logic. |
| **Debounce/Throttle** | Not shown here, but recommended for performance. |
| **State Management** | Tracks `page`, `loading`, and `hasMore` states. |
| **Ref for Intersection Observer** | Ensures the observer is properly cleaned up. |

---

## 📌 Notes:

- **Avoid infinite scroll on every scroll**, use `hasMore` to prevent unnecessary API calls.
- You can use `IntersectionObserver` instead of `window.scroll` for better performance and UX.
- For real-world apps, consider using **React Hooks like `useInfiniteScroll`** (from libraries like `react-infinite-scroll-component`) for cleaner code.

---

## 🚀 Optional: Use a Library

If you want a more elegant solution, you can use:

```bash
npm install react-infinite-scroll-component
```

Then:

```jsx
import InfiniteScroll from 'react-infinite-scroll-component';

const ProductList = () => {
  const [products, setProducts] = useState([]);
  const [page, setPage] = useState(1);

  const fetchProducts = async () => {
    // fetch products from API
  };

  return (
    <InfiniteScroll
      dataLength={products.length}
      next={fetchProducts}
      hasMore={hasMore}
      loader={<div>Loading...</div>}
    >
      {products.map((product, index) => (
        <div key={index}>{product.name}</div>
      ))}
    </InfiniteScroll>
  );
};
```

---

## 📌 Summary

| Method | Pros | Cons |
|-------|------|------|
| IntersectionObserver | Efficient, modern | Slightly more complex |
| Scroll Event | Simple, compatible | Can be slow on heavy scroll |
| Library (e.g., `react-infinite-scroll-component`) | Easy, clean | Adds external dependency |

---

