One solution to this issue would be to update the text in the `controller` after the formatter has been applied. You can do this by listening to the `TextField`'s `onChanged` callback, and updating the `controller.text` property there.

Here is an example of how you can do this:
```
TextEditingController _controller = TextEditingController();

...

TextField(
  controller: _controller,
  inputFormatters: [
    MaskedTextInputFormatter(
      mask: '0000-0000-0000-0000',
      separator: '-',
    ),
  ],
  onChanged: (text) {
    _controller.text = text;
  },
)
```
In this example, the `onChanged` callback is used to update the `controller.text` property with the current input text. This ensures that the mask is applied to the text even if it is set from a local file.

Alternatively, you can set the controller value after applying the formatter, like this:
```
String phone = "1234567890";
_controller.text = MaskedTextInputFormatter(mask: '000-000-0000').formatEditUpdate(
    new TextEditingValue(text: phone),
    new TextEditingValue(text: phone)
);
