When using React Native and Firebase, best practices for handling authenticated sessions and displaying a user's name include the following steps:

1. Install Firebase and Firebase authentication packages in your React Native project.
2. Initialize Firebase and set up authentication methods according to your requirements.
3. Use React Navigation and create an authentication flow for your app, which usually includes sign-up, sign-in, and sign-out screens.
4. Use `onAuthStateChanged` listener provided by Firebase to listen for authentication state changes. This listener will be called when the user logs in or out, and it can be used to manage the authenticated session.

Here's an example of how you can implement these steps:

1. Install Firebase and Firebase authentication packages:
```bash
npm install firebase
npm install @react-native-firebase/app
npm install @react-native-firebase/auth
```
1. Initialize Firebase and set up authentication methods:
```javascript
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/auth';

const firebaseConfig = {
  // Your Firebase configuration
};

if (!firebase.apps.length) {
  firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
}
```
1. Set up the authentication flow with React Navigation.
2. Use the `onAuthStateChanged` listener:
```javascript
import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { Text, View } from 'react-native';
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/auth';

const App = () => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const unsubscribe = firebase.auth().onAuthStateChanged((user) => {
      if (user) {
        setUser(user);
      } else {
        setUser(null);
      }
    });

    return () => {
      unsubscribe();
    };
  }, []);

  if (user) {
    return (
      <View>
        <Text>Welcome, {user.displayName || user.email}</Text>
        // Render your app's authenticated views here
      </View>
    );
  } else {
    return (
      <View>
        // Render your app's sign-up and sign-in screens here
      </View>
    );
  }
};

export default App;
```
In this example, the `user` state is updated whenever the user logs in or out. When the `user` state has a value, it means the user is logged in, and you can display their name using `user.displayName` or `user.email` as a fallback. When the `user` state is `null`, it means the user is not logged in, and you can render the sign-up and sign-in screens.

Yes, using a context provider to manage the user's authentication state is a good idea. It allows you to share the user's state across your app's components without passing it down through props. Here's an example of how you can create an authentication context:

1. Create a new file called `AuthContext.js` and add the following code:
```javascript
import React, { createContext, useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/auth';

export const AuthContext = createContext();

export const AuthProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const unsubscribe = firebase.auth().onAuthStateChanged((user) => {
      if (user) {
        setUser(user);
      } else {
        setUser(null);
      }
    });

    return () => {
      unsubscribe();
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
};
```
1. Wrap your app's root component with the `AuthProvider`:
```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { NavigationContainer } from '@react-navigation/native';
import { createStackNavigator } from '@react-navigation/stack';
import { AuthProvider } from './AuthContext';
import HomeScreen from './screens/HomeScreen';
import SignInScreen from './screens/SignInScreen';
import SignUpScreen from './screens/SignUpScreen';

const Stack = createStackNavigator();

const App = () => {
  return (
    <NavigationContainer>
      <AuthProvider>
        <Stack.Navigator>
          <Stack.Screen name="Home" component={HomeScreen} />
          <Stack.Screen name="Sign In" component={SignInScreen} />
          <Stack.Screen name="Sign Up" component={SignUpScreen} />
        </Stack.Navigator>
      </AuthProvider>
    </NavigationContainer>
  );
};

export default App;
```
1. Use the `AuthContext` in any component that needs access to the user's state:
```javascript
import React, { useContext } from 'react';
import { View, Text } from 'react-native';
import { AuthContext } from '../AuthContext';

const HomeScreen = () => {
  const { user } = useContext(AuthContext);

  if (user) {
    return (
      <View>
        <Text>Welcome, {user.displayName || user.email}</Text>
        // Render your app's authenticated views here
      </View>
    );
  } else {
    return (
      <View>
        // Render your app's sign-up and sign-in screens here
      </View>
    );
  }
};

export default HomeScreen;
```
Now the user's authentication state is accessible across your app's components, and you can use the `AuthContext` to manage the state consistently.

