## 📌 Step 3: Arduino Sketch (Example)

Here's a sample Arduino sketch that sends ESC RPM and temperature data every 100 ms using the MAVLink v2 protocol:

```cpp
#include <SPI.h>
#include <HardwareSerial.h>
#include <mavlink.h>
#include "mavlink_msg_esc_status_encode.h"  // Generated from ESC_STATUS.msg

// Define serial port (for example, using hardware serial)
HardwareSerial serialPort(USB); // For Teensy 3.x
// HardwareSerial serialPort(1); // For Teensy 4.x, using Serial1

// MAVLink system ID and component ID
uint8_t system_id = 1;
uint8_t component_id = 1;

void setup() {
  // Initialize serial communication
  serialPort.begin(57600);
  while (!serialPort) { /* Wait for serial port to be ready */ }

  // Set up MAVLink 2.0
  mavlink_set_system_id_and_component(&serialPort, system_id, component_id);
}

void loop() {
  // Simulate ESC RPM and temperature (you can read from sensors)
  uint16_t rpm = 12345; // Replace with actual RPM data
  uint16_t temperature = 45; // Replace with actual temperature data

  // Create and send the custom message
  mavlink_message_t msg;
  uint8_t buf[MAVLINK_MAX_PACKET_LEN];

  mavlink_msg_esc_status_pack(system_id, component_id, &msg, rpm, temperature);

  uint16_t len = mavlink_msg_to_send_buffer(buf, &msg);

  serialPort.write(buf, len);

  delay(100); // Send every 100 ms
}
```

